\begin{multicols}{2}
\textit{\textbf{Abstract}}—\textbf{The paper considers the main directions, problems, and prospects for the development of next- generation intelligent computer systems and corresponding technologies, with a focus on the current state of work in the field of Artificial Intelligence. It highlights the problems and methodological challenges of the current stage of development, as well as the prerequisites for transitioning to intelligent computer systems of the new generation. The text also provides background and history of OSTIS Technology development, and outlines its features, advantages, and novelty. Additionally, it mentions current projects related to the development of OSTIS Technology in the current stage of work.}

\setcounter{page}{15}

\textbf{\textit{Keywords}—Next-generation intelligent computer system, self-learning intelligent computer system, interoperable intelligent computer system, individual subject, collective of subjects, hierarchical subject, social responsibility\textasciicircum , interoperability\textasciicircum , individual activity, collective activity, intelligence of a collective of subjects\textasciicircum , strategic problem of the subject\textasteriskcentered, subproblem\textasteriskcentered, Society, OSTIS Ecosystem .}

\begin{center}
\label{1}\textsc{I.   The feature of the current state of work in the field of Artificial intelligence—is the transition to the next-generation intelligent computer systems.}\\
\end{center}
The epicenter of the modern stage of automation of human activity is a low level of automation and high overhead costs
\begin{itemize}
    \item for the system integration of various computer systems, in other words, for the creation of complicated hierarchical computer complexes;
    \item \hyperref[1]{for the modernization of computer systems during their operation [1].}
\end{itemize}


Modern computer systems clearly lack the \textit{intelligence} and \textit{autonomy} to automate these aspects of human activity.


The necessity to move from modern \textit{computer systems} (including modern \textit{intelligent computer systems}) to next-
generation \textit{intelligent computer systems} is due to the necessity to move to automate more and more complex types and areas of \textit{human activity} requiring the creation of whole complexes of \textit{intelligent computer systems} that
can independently \uline{evolve} and \uline{interact} effectively with each other in the \textit{\uline{collective} solution of complex problems.}


Computer systems with these abilities are the \textit{new
generation computer systems}. Since these \textit{computer systems} cannot but have a high level of \textit{intelligence}, they should also be referred to as \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems}. A high level of \textit{intelligence} is necessary for next-generation computer systems:
\begin{itemize}
    \item to adequately assessment their own competence and the competence of their partners; 
    \item to ensure mutual understanding, contractual capacity and coordination (consistency) of their actions with the actions of partners in the course of \textit{collective solution of complex problems} in the conditions of possible occurrence of unpredictable (non-standard) circumstances.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{next-generation intelligent computer system}

\large
\noindent=
\normalsize
\hfill{\textit{(self-learning intelligent computer system} $\cap$}


\hyperref[2]{\hfill{\textit{interoperable intelligent computer system}) [2]}}


\noindent\textbf{self-learning intelligent computer system}

\large
\noindent:=
\normalsize
\begin{flushright}
\vspace{-1.56\baselineskip}
[\textit{an intelligent computer system} that has a high\\rate of \uline{self-realized} evolution, which results in\\a significant reduction in the complexity (costs,\\overhead) of its \uline{modernization}]
\end{flushright}
\noindent\textbf{self-learning of an intelligent computer system}

\large
$\Rightarrow$
\normalsize
\textit{suggests}\textasteriskcentered:
\newpage
\setcounter{page}{16}
\begin{itemize}
    \item ability to monitor the state and dynamics of the environment and adjust their actions with appropriate environmental changes (adaptability);
    \item ability to analyze and improve the quality of your own knowledge base (structuring and analysis of contradictions, information holes, information garbage);
    \item ability to extract knowledge from external sources of information;
    \item ability to analyze and improve the quality of their own activities (including the ability to learn from their own mistakes);
    \item ability to analyze the quality of the activities of other subjects and benefit from it for yourself (learn from the mistakes of others).
\end{itemize}
\noindent\textbf{high level of self-learning of an intelligent computer system}


\large
$\Rightarrow$
\normalsize
\textit{is provided by}\textasteriskcentered:


\begin{flushright}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item high level of flexibility of an intelligent computer system
        \item high level of stratification of an intelligent computer system
        \item high level of reflexivity of an intelligent computer system
        \item high level of cognitive activity
    \end{itemize}
\end{flushright}


\noindent\textbf{interoperable intelligent computer system}


\large
:=
\normalsize
\begin{flushright}
\vspace{-1.75\baselineskip}
    [computer system capable of\\\uline{independent} effective interaction with other systems]
\end{flushright}


\noindent\textbf{interoperability of an intelligent computer system}


\large
$\Rightarrow$
\normalsize
\textit{suggests}\textasteriskcentered:
\begin{itemize}
    \item ability to \uline{understand} other systems and
its users
\end{itemize}
    \begin{center}
        \large
        \vspace{-0.5\baselineskip}
        \hspace{-5cm}$\Rightarrow$
        \normalsize
        \textit{suggests}\textasteriskcentered:
        \begin{flushright}
            semantic compatibility with\\
interacting systems and users
        \end{flushright}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item \uline{negotiability}
            \item \uline{ability to coordinate} their actions with the actions of partners
        \end{itemize}
    \end{center}

Our proposed approach to the construction of the next- generation intelligent computer systems is based on the following principles:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \uline{semantic} representation of knowledge stored in the memory of \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems};
    \item \uline{ontological} structuring and systematization of knowledge stored in memory;
    \item \uline{decentralized} situational agent-oriented organization of \textit{problem solving processes};
    \item \uline{convergence} and deep (diffuse) integration of various
problem solving models and, as a consequence, the
hybrid nature of \textit{problem solvers};
    \item \uline{semantic integration} of input information entering
an individual intelligent computer system from the outside through different sensory channels and in different languages by translating input information into a common universal \textit{language of internal semantic representation of knowledge}..
\end{itemize}


