\begin{center}
\label{2}\textsc{II.   Problems of the current stage of development of the theory and technology of next-generation intelligent computer systems.}
\end{center}
The creation of \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems} requires answers to the following questions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item What are the requirements for \textit{intelligent computer systems} that provide the above \uline{complex} automation of\textit{ human activities};
    \item Why modern intelligent computer systems do not meet these requirements and, accordingly, why the transition to a fundamentally \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems is necessary};
    \item What fundamental principles should underlie the \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems};
    \item What principles should underlie the \uline{most automated technology} for designing and supporting the entire life cycle of \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems};
    \item What principles should underlie the structure and organization of various types and areas of \textit{human activity} to ensure its comprehensive and maximum possible automation with the help of \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems} (as you know, before automating any \textit{human activity}, it is necessary to put it in order — automating disorder leads to even greater disorder).
\end{itemize}
The current fundamental problems of creating the theory and technology of \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems} include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Development of a \uline{theory} of hierarchical \textit{multi-agent systems} in which agents are individual or collective \textit{intelligent computer systems that are interoperable}.
    \item \uline{Unification} and \uline{standardization} of various models of knowledge representation and processing. The effect of this unification will not be visible immediately. But if this does not happen, we will never come to an effective \uline{comprehensive automation} of \textit{human activity}. The eclectic variety of automation methods and tools leads not only to unjustified \uline{duplication} of the systems being developed, but also to an increase in the complexity of their use and maintenance.
    \item \uline{Convergence} and \uline{integration} of different areas of \textit{Artificial Intelligence}.
Currently, various areas of \textit{Artificial Intelligence} have a fairly high level of development (signal processing, natural language processing, logical models, artificial neural networks, ontological models, multi-agent models, and many others). Integration of all these directions is a rather time-consuming problem, but it is quite a solvable one, which is based on the harmonization of related notions.
    \item \uline{Convergence} of such activities in the field of\textit{ Artificial Intelligence} as:
\end{itemize}
– training of specialists in the field of \textit{Artificial
Intelligence};\\
– engineering activities for the development of applied \textit{next-generation intelligent computer systems};\\
– development of \textit{technology} for designing and supporting the life cycle of \textit{next-generation intelligent
computer systems};\\
– research activities in the field of \textit{Artificial intelligence}.
\begin{itemize}
    \item In order to develop the Technology of \textit{next-
generation intelligent computer systems}, it is also necessary to \uline{converge} this Technology \uline{with all}
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

